<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,260,1184]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis box="[197,331,1016,1040]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,324,1016,1040]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Etymology</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The name is a patronymic for Dr. Michael Sharkey, University of Kentucky for his work on the 
<collectingCountry box="[151,261,1052,1076]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Colombia</collectingCountry>
leafhopper fauna and providing much material for study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,260,1184]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis box="[197,313,1088,1112]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,306,1088,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
This species is closest to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nielson" authorityYear="1979" box="[604,698,1089,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Baluba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[604,698,1089,1112]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">B. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and can be distinguished by the prominent, subapical lateral lobe on the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[350,435,1124,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–24" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[225,1343,237,1849]" captionTargetId="figure-70@11.[202,1368,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 17–24. Baluba sharkeyi, sp. nov. (17) pygofer and segment X, lateral view; (18) right subgenital plate, ventral view; (19) right style, lateral view; (20) right style, dorsal view; (21) aedeagus and dorsal connective, lateral view; (22) aedeagus, ventral view; (23) connective, dorsal view; (24) dorsal connective, dorsal view." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), the long caudodorsal process of the pygofer (
<figureCitation box="[975,1057,1124,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–24" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[225,1343,237,1849]" captionTargetId="figure-70@11.[202,1368,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 17–24. Baluba sharkeyi, sp. nov. (17) pygofer and segment X, lateral view; (18) right subgenital plate, ventral view; (19) right style, lateral view; (20) right style, dorsal view; (21) aedeagus and dorsal connective, lateral view; (22) aedeagus, ventral view; (23) connective, dorsal view; (24) dorsal connective, dorsal view." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) and the long, narrow subgenital plate (
<figureCitation box="[220,304,1160,1184]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–24" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[225,1343,237,1849]" captionTargetId="figure-70@11.[202,1368,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 17–24. Baluba sharkeyi, sp. nov. (17) pygofer and segment X, lateral view; (18) right subgenital plate, ventral view; (19) right style, lateral view; (20) right style, dorsal view; (21) aedeagus and dorsal connective, lateral view; (22) aedeagus, ventral view; (23) connective, dorsal view; (24) dorsal connective, dorsal view." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
